demand: How fairly you divide money against different people
comment: It was a hard experiment in gaining a profit, because all participants want to gain more and always one participant gets unfair payment.

demand: Whether people who identified with left-wing political views would allocate money "fairly" or not.
To see how sustainable could be cooperation. In this experiment, however, everyone is induce to maximize his own actual utility.
Division between poor and rich people, and even though you have certain beliefes almost everyone always wants to make him- or herself rich.
comment: It was okay, a bit slow sometimes.

demand: About either trying to reach the highest sum for yourself or trying to divide it equally between the three participants.
comment: Interesting experiment as it shows pretty well that we prefer keeping the maximum of the money personnally even though one of the participants was affected

demand: The experiment was about seeing how people act and treat others when they have a certain amount of power (in this case indicated by money and by the fact that the can not be traced back or identified and that every time the people you relate with change). Also, the experiment was about seeing how a person that defines herself being "left" or "right" politically speaking acts when she has the concrete power to make thing go how she wants.
comment: The mechanism was easy to understand this time, you just needed to give a reasonable amount of money from the 17<a3> to one of the others in your group and since you just needed two people to accept the offer was pretty clear that things were going to go as you wanted if your proposal had been selected.

demand: In my opinion the experiment was about making financial decisions in different situations
comment: I think this experiment could be very helpful for those who carry out studies about this kind of things
I thought it was well structured and enjoyable.

demand:
To see if people were able to agree on a decision : it is easier when the amount given to each participant is more or less alike, but if one is disadvantaged and not the two others, the two others may still agree on the deal.
Plus, the teams were formed by three people, meaning one of them is always the one who proposed the deal, so they will accept it
comment: Long, a lot of waiting between each session.
degree: In France, my degree's called LLCE Anglais, meaning I'm studying British & American Language, Literature and Civilization.

demand: Im not too sure, think it was about looking at individuals decision making when money is involved and the best way in which they can receive most money
Greed? Maybe it was about the choices people make, whether they are fair or not. What others would do in terms of their economic interests.
comment: It was good, just didn't like when I was allocated anything in terms of money. I guess it was beneficial for both parties except me, can't fault them it's human nature. Now I hope I'm allocated something.

demand: How someone tends to divide money when themselves are included in the group.
comment: Interesting. Not hard to understand the concept or instructions. Would be interested in reading about the results.

demand: i think it was about the idea of how people can share a particular sum of money between each of money and how to make it fair.
comment: I think it was very interesting and I would happily do it again.

demand: I think it was about how groups handle investments and and see if the participants try to share the money to gain as much as possible. (and if so, how)
comment: I think it was a bit unfair that we were in groups of 3, as the participant who submits his proposition will obviously accept it, so as others we have no chance of fairness.

demand: I would assume that the experiment was testing participants' choices in a scenario where being overly greedy may result in risking receiving any income. I therefore was trying to find balance in the amount of money allocated for others and myself to maximize my gain and offer the others bare safe minimum.
comment: This was one of the most engaging experiments I have attended so far. Obviously the same set back as always is the dragging speed (or lack of) due to some participants, however I am satisfied with the experience.

demand: I think the experiment was about the types of decisions we make depending on our situations.
comment: I thought the experiment was very clever in how it encouraged independence within our decisions, it allowed us to have complete freedom and control over the decisions we made. I think the experiment also allows us to see what kind of person we can be depending on our roles within the group we were put in, and how we would act within these groups.
